it's not a full computer, don't expect it to be. it's excellent for surfing the web, viewing ipad optimized videos, and have great apps. apple didn't include a front facing camera because it wants to save those features future product releases. i know this is cruel of apple but you'll just have to live with it. best tablet on the market and no other tablet even compares. the blackberry playbook might give the ipad a run for its money if it's ever released. i am certain apple will launch a new model by the same the playbook is out.
After using the iPad for a few months I agree with the predominant points I see here, that this is a nice device, a pleasure to use, with some drawbacks (single threading and speed) and a Kindle competitor, but not a Kindle killer.I would add that in my experience typing is a big concern. I like to type on mobile devices so one of my first concerns was whether I could use the virtual keyboard. I was pleasantly surprised that the keys, in landscape mode, are just in the right place and I can basically touch type. I did buy the dock with its real keyboard but don't use it. The screen keyboard is very effective for me.Another pleasant surprise I got is that, while I agree that this is not the end-all for e-reading (vs. the Kindle and such), it is outstanding for video. With streaming services such as Netflix it can be a nice TV and movie viewer for a single viewer or even two people.Finally the reason I gave it four stars rather than five is because I am a heavy user of my iTouch and the iPad doesn't add a whole lot to the experience. For me I measure the value of the iPad against the iTouch which I had been a big user of for over a year before I bought the iPad. The iPad does offer the touch typing that I can't nearly match on the iTouch. I can only thumb-type (at best) on the iTouch so the iPad offers a real writing experience against the clumsy iPod typing experience. But otherwise the iPad just doesn't get a lot of use for my set of apps because of size. I have the iPod with me all of the time and the iPad is larger so I only use it at home as a lightweight laptop substitute.In summary I'd say Apple made a good, very appealing product. I would recommend it to an Apple fan or someone who wants an outstanding web browsing and video experience. A particular strength is the browser which has the legendary multi-touch interface in the iTouch plus the better screen real estate. I would say it is the best plain browsing experience I have had on any device. Kudos to Apple for wedging a product in that in-between category against laptops and netbooks.
Very happy with it especially during my business calls. I use in it in place of a daytimer for notes, follow-ups, and emails.It works for me!
On the whole not a bad device at all. Very ease to carry around and use just about anywhere and don't be put off with what you hear about this device not cutting it as a real productivity business tool. Yes granted it does not come out of the box with everything necessary for the average business man to do a "honest" days. Work but the right tools to get the job done are available.Just a couple of things Steve, a camera might go down a treat in the next itteration of this device and the most annoying thing so far to come to mind is the version of Safari running on this device is seen by many sites as a mobile version and even after using a browser which masquerades as another browser some sites still see the device as mobile which is rather limiting.The Bluetooth services work well with one exception that the older Apple bluetooth keyboards do not pair with this device. I guess it's time for me to donate to the coffers of Apple again. (no only joking Steve :) mine is getting a bit long in the tooth any way.I really do beleive this is a the turning point in the evolution of the tablet based device. Can't wait to see the next step in it's creation. Well Done! Steve and all of your innovative staff and associates.
