Okay, I don't own it but I am tech-savvy enough to understand this device after reading reviews, after seeing product specifications, AND after playing with a friend's iPad for sometime. So I think I can write a review here!I don't think this device is worth the steep price! Wait for the upcoming Android or Windows based tablets. If you want functional devices then stay away from iPads! My $250 Toshiba netbook is far more functional than the cheapest iPad of $500. Heck, iPad does not even have a standard USB port (my Toshiba has THREE!). For iPad, you are supposed to dish out some (MORE) hard earned money to get an Apple-approved gadget to get the USB functionality. See how you are being fleeced?Don't fall for the Apple hype. Educate yourselves about what you are about to buy/into. Yes, iPAD is very fluid and my Toshiba can't match that fluidity. But the Toshiba is adequate for web surfing, easier to handle (light weight), has a physical keyboard, and has a 6-cell battery which lasts 5-6+ hours. And, running Windows 7, it has access to tens of thousands of free and time-tested Windows software out there.One more myth-busting about Windows: The Toshiba has NEVER been infected by viruses or trojans even though it does not run any anti-virus software. I take it to public places and hook up to public WiFi, still no issues. No 'Blue Screen of Death' either. It's been at least 10 months of trouble-free ownership for me!If you are looking for tablets, then might as well want to read the following "user" comment made about HP Slate 500 which is coming out. This is from the Hewlett Packard's Slate 500. I will keep checking Amazon for HP Slate 500 or other non-Apple tablet devices.PS. I know Apple fanbois are not going to like my comment but so be it! Apple gets free pass in the media and that is not good to inform users about Apple's crippled products. Some of us are starting to challenge that.[Quote Begin]"Nice device  Date: November 8, 2010"can iPad join windows domain con